_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n M1-M8\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n<p class=\"p\">SQL_DOUBLE</p>\n</td>\n</tr><tr class=\"row even\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n N1-N32\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n SQL_NUMERIC\n <p class=\"p\">SQL_DECIMAL</p>\n</td>\n</tr><tr class=\"row odd\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n F4\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n SQL_REAL\n <p class=\"p\">SQL_FLOAT</p>\n</td>\n</tr><tr class=\"row even\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n F8\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n SQL_DOUBLE\n <p class=\"p\">SQL_FLOAT</p>\n</td>\n</tr><tr class=\"row odd\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n D1-D16\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n SQL_TYPE_DATE\n <p class=\"p\">SQL_DATE</p>\n</td>\n</tr><tr class=\"row even\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n E1-E16\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n SQL_TYPE_TIMESTAMP\n <p class=\"p\">SQL_TIMESTAMP</p>\n</td>\n</tr><tr class=\"row odd\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n T1-T16\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n SQL_TYPE_TIME\n <p class=\"p\">SQL_TIME</p>\n</td>\n</tr><tr class=\"row even\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__1\">\n B1-B8\n </td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\" headers=\"dea1665702954078__table_d5075e1_d5076e1_d5077e1__entry__2\">\n<p class=\"p\">SQL_BIT</p>\n</td>\n</tr></tbody></table></div><div class=\"dataTables_scrollFoot\" style=\"overflow: hidden; border: 0px; width: 100%;\"><div class=\"dataTables_scrollFootInner\"><table class=\"table dataTable no-footer\" count-columns=\"2\" style=\"margin-left: 0px;\"><tfoot></tfoot></table></div></div></div></div></div>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"dea1665702954078__topic_d36367e1_d36368e1_d36369e1_d36370e1_d36371e1\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d1035561e408\">\n                        \n Overflow Tables\n </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"dea1665702954078__p_d55007e1_d55008e1_d55009e1\">The following Uniface packing codes require an overflow table when a large amount of data is inserted into the field:</p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dea1665702954078__li_d25334e1_d25335e1_d25336e1\">C*\n </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dea1665702954078__li_d25337e1_d25338e1_d25339e1\">VC*\n </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dea1665702954078__li_d25340e1_d25341e1_d25342e1\">U*\n </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dea1665702954078__li_d25343e1_d25344e1_d25345e1\">VU*\n </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dea1665702954078__li_d25346e1_d25347e1_d25348e1\">R*\n </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"dea1665702954078__li_d25349e1_d25350e1_d25351e1\">VR*\n </li>\n</ul>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div><div class=\"contentPlaceholder\" style=\"height: 500px;\"><div class=\"contentContainer zDocsSideBoxes\"><div><h5 aria-level=\"5\" class=\"css-g931ng\">Related Links</h5><ul><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/wop1665702530947.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Storage Formats</a><p>DBMS vendors use the term data type to describe the way data is handled and stored on disk, but this invariably means the way the data is actually stored. In Uniface documentation, the term storage format is therefore used to refer to DBMS data types . A Uniface data type is specified for each field in a modeled entity; a DBMS storage format is internal to the DBMS.</p></li><li><a class=\"css-ettsdk\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/uww1665702531035.html\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-related-link\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-related-link\"></use></svg>Packing Codes</a><p>Packing codes are mappings between Uniface data types and DBMS data types (storage formats). When writing a field, Uniface passes the data and a valid packing code to the DBMS connector, which uses the packing code to determine the appropriate storage format for storing the data in the target DBMS. Packing codes also determine how data is interfaced with 3GL routines.</p></li></ul></div></div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2526759\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2526759\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "ODBC Data Packing Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Okt 07, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 ODBC Data Packing The Uniface ODBC configurator determines what storage format (data type) the DBMS supports. For any format the DBMS does not support, the connector uses the default storage format. For more information about the storage formats used by ODBC, see your DBMS documentation and your ODBC documentation. Search: Column Uniface Packing Code ODBC Storage Format 1 Filter results... 22 rows found Export to Excel Export to CSV Table 1. Mappings Between Uniface Packing Codes and ODBC Storage Formats Uniface Packing Code ODBC Storage Format 1 Filter 22 rows found Filter 22 rows found Uniface Packing Code ODBC Storage Format 1 C1-C* SQL_WVARCHAR SQL_VARCHAR SQL_WCHAR SQL_CHAR VC1-VC* SQL_WVARCHAR SQL_VARCHAR SQL_WCHAR SQL_CHAR SC1-SC* SQL_WLONGVARCHAR SQL_LONGVARCHAR SQL_WVARCHAR SQL_VARCHAR SQL_WCHAR SQL_CHAR U1-U* SQL_WVARCHAR SQL_VARCHAR SQL_WCHAR SQL_CHAR VU1-VU* SQL_WVARCHAR SQL_VARCHAR SQL_WCHAR SQL_CHAR SU1-SU* 2 SQL_WLONGVARCHAR SQL_LONGVARCHAR SQL_WVARCHAR SQL_VARCHAR SQL_WCHAR SQL_CHAR R1-R* SQL_BINARY SR1-SR* 2 SQL_LONGVARBINARY SQL_VARBINARY SQL_BINARY VR1-VR* SQL_VARBINARY SQL_BINARY I1 SQL_TINYINT 2 SQL_SMALLINT SQL_INT I2 SQL_SMALLINT SQL_INT I3 SQL_INT I4 SQL_INT I8 SQL_BIGINT M1-M8 SQL_DOUBLE N1-N32 SQL_NUMERIC SQL_DECIMAL F4 SQL_REAL SQL_FLOAT F8 SQL_DOUBLE SQL_FLOAT D1-D16 SQL_TYPE_DATE SQL_DATE E1-E16 SQL_TYPE_TIMESTAMP SQL_TIMESTAMP T1-T16 SQL_TYPE_TIME SQL_TIME B1-B8 SQL_BIT Overflow Tables The following Uniface packing codes require an overflow table when a large amount of data is inserted into the field: C* VC* U* VU* R* VR* Related Links Storage Formats DBMS vendors use the term data type to describe the way data is handled and stored on disk, but this invariably means the way the data is actually stored. In Uniface documentation, the term storage format is therefore used to refer to DBMS data types . A Uniface data type is specified for each field in a modeled entity; a DBMS storage format is internal to the DBMS. Packing Codes Packing codes are mappings between Uniface data types and DBMS data types (storage formats). When writing a field, Uniface passes the data and a valid packing code to the DBMS connector, which uses the packing code to determine the appropriate storage format for storing the data in the target DBMS. Packing codes also determine how data is interfaced with 3GL routines. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}